{"insight":"Do Not Make Performance Your Only Shelter","publicTitle":"When Performance Can No Longer Hold You","plainSummary":"A life held only by effort can fall harder, so build ties, rhythms, and promises that steady you before collapse.","atAGlance":"A person can seem steady because they are performing well. When that performance breaks, they may find too little else to lean on. The work is to let body, trusted people, daily rhythms, and honest duties share the weight early. But for those harmed by control or false surrender, help must restore strength, not erase it.","keyPoints":["Meaning can live in relationships, habits, promises, and the body.","Leaning outward can harm people whose strength was already taken from them.","Test whether self-held lives break harder under grief, burnout, or failure."],"match":["what holds you"],"tags":["burnout","grief","practice","support"]}
